Matrix Equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The algebraic equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x-7=5
\]

\end_inset

is commonly solved by adding 
\begin_inset Formula $7$
\end_inset

 to both sides of the equation.
 The reason this works is because 
\begin_inset Formula $-7+7=0$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $7$
\end_inset

 is the additive inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $-7$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $x+0=x$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is the additive identity).
 In linear algebra there is an additive identity matrix (theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:matrixproperties-part1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 claim 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:additive-identity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and there are additive inverses (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:operation-properties"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 exercise 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "exc:additive-inverse"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), so analogous equations ought to be solvable similarly.
 Indeed they are! The matrix equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X-\left[\begin{array}{cc}
7 & 1\\
-3 & 8
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
5 & -3\\
2 & 4
\end{array}\right]\label{eq:first-matrix-equation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

can be solved by the same process.
 Adding 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cc}
7 & 1\\
-3 & 8
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 to both sides of the equation gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
X-\left[\begin{array}{cc}
7 & 1\\
-3 & 8
\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{cc}
7 & 1\\
-3 & 8
\end{array}\right] & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
5 & -3\\
2 & 4
\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{cc}
7 & 1\\
-3 & 8
\end{array}\right]\\
X+\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right] & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
5+7 & -3+1\\
2-3 & 4+8
\end{array}\right]\\
X & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
12 & -2\\
-1 & 12
\end{array}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cc}
12 & -2\\
-1 & 12
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:first-matrix-equation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) yields a true statement, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cc}
12 & -2\\
-1 & 12
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 is a solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The slightly more advanced equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
8x-7=5
\]

\end_inset

is commonly solved by first adding 
\begin_inset Formula $7$
\end_inset

 to both sides and then dividing both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

 (or equivalently multiplying both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{8}$
\end_inset

, the multiplicative inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

).
 This might be demonstrated as follows.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
8x-7 & =5\\
8x-7+7 & =5+7\\
8x & =12\\
\frac{8x}{8} & =\frac{12}{8}\\
x & =\frac{3}{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This method works because, in addtion to the facts that 
\begin_inset Formula $-7$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $7$
\end_inset

 are additive inverses and 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is the additive identity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{8}{8}=1$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{8}$
\end_inset

 are multiplicative inverses) and 
\begin_inset Formula $1x=x$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is the multiplicative identity).
 In linear algebra, there are multiplicative identity matrices and there
 are multiplicative inverses (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Matrix-Division"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), so analogous equations ought to be solvable similarly.
 Indeed they are! The matrix equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
9 & 4\\
4 & 2
\end{array}\right]X-\left[\begin{array}{cc}
7 & 1\\
-3 & 8
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
5 & -3\\
2 & 4
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

can be solved by the same process.
 Adding 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cc}
7 & 1\\
-3 & 8
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 to both sides of the equation and then (left) multiplying both sides by
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cc}
9 & 4\\
4 & 2
\end{array}\right]^{-1}$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
9 & 4\\
4 & 2
\end{array}\right]X-\left[\begin{array}{cc}
7 & 1\\
-3 & 8
\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{cc}
7 & 1\\
-3 & 8
\end{array}\right] & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
5 & -3\\
2 & 4
\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{cc}
7 & 1\\
-3 & 8
\end{array}\right]\\
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
9 & 4\\
4 & 2
\end{array}\right]X & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
12 & -2\\
-1 & 12
\end{array}\right]\\
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
9 & 4\\
4 & 2
\end{array}\right]^{-1}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
9 & 4\\
4 & 2
\end{array}\right]X & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
9 & 4\\
4 & 2
\end{array}\right]^{-1}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
12 & -2\\
-1 & 12
\end{array}\right]\\
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & -2\\
-2 & \frac{9}{2}
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
9 & 4\\
4 & 2
\end{array}\right]X & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & -2\\
-2 & \frac{9}{2}
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
12 & -2\\
-1 & 12
\end{array}\right]\\
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right]X & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
14 & -26\\
\frac{-57}{2} & 58
\end{array}\right]\\
X & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
14 & -26\\
\frac{-57}{2} & 58
\end{array}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cc}
14 & -26\\
\frac{-57}{2} & 58
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in the original equation yields a true statement, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cc}
14 & -26\\
\frac{-57}{2} & 58
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 is a solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It seems as though the familiar ideas of adding, subtracting, multiplying,
 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dividing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 both sides of an equation are valid steps in solving matrix equations,
 but better not to take it for granted on the back of a pair of examples
 where it works.
 In adding a matrix to both sides of an equation (or subtracting a matrix
 from both sides of an equation) in an attempt to solve it, we are using
 the principle that for matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,C$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{if }A=B\text{ then }A+C=B+C\label{eq:addition-property-of-equality}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

whenever the indicated operations are defined.
 Since the veracity of this proposition is critical to the logical validity
 of the solutions above, solid proof is warranted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The principle of equality suggested in exercise 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "exc:definition-of-equality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 of section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:operation-properties"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is useful.
 It says that 
\begin_inset Formula $A=B$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $A-B=0$
\end_inset

.
 That is, if we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $A=B$
\end_inset

, we can safely say that 
\begin_inset Formula $A-B=0$
\end_inset

.
 And if we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $A-B=0$
\end_inset

, we can safely say that 
\begin_inset Formula $A=B$
\end_inset

.
 Hopefully that sounds logical whether you have completed exercise 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "exc:definition-of-equality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 or not.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Getting back to proposition (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:addition-property-of-equality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), note that it begins with the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $A=B$
\end_inset

.
 By the principle of equality we can immediately deduce that 
\begin_inset Formula $0=A-B$
\end_inset

.
 Now because 
\begin_inset Formula $C-C=0$
\end_inset

 for any matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is the additive identity, we can proceed as follows.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =A-B\\
 & =(A-B)+0\\
 & =(A-B)+(C-C)\\
 & =((A-B)+C)-C\\
 & =(A+(-B+C))-C\\
 & =(A+(C-B))-C\\
 & =((A+C)-B)-C\\
 & =(A+C)+(-B-C)\\
 & =(A+C)-(B+C)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We have used associativity and commutativity for addition of matrices as
 well as the distributive property as well.
 Now that we have 
\begin_inset Formula $0=(A+C)-(B+C)$
\end_inset

 we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $A+C=B+C$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equally critical to the second solution above is the principle that for
 matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,C$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{if }A=B\text{ then }CA=CB\label{eq:multiplication-property-of-equality-part-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

whenever the indicated operations are defined.
 The proof is very similar to the proof of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:addition-property-of-equality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $A=B$
\end_inset

 allows us to proceed with 
\begin_inset Formula $0=A-B$
\end_inset

, but this time we employ the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $C0=0$
\end_inset

 for any matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 (exercise 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "exc:zero-products"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 of section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:operation-properties"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =A-B\\
 & =C(A-B)\\
 & =CA-CB
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $CA=CB$
\end_inset

.
 It is also true that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{if }A=B\text{ then }AC=BC\label{eq:multiplication-property-of-equality-part-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

whenever the indicated operations are defined.
 Why is this claim needed? Can you justify this claim? Answers on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:mult-property-of-equality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Stmbolic equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The need to solve a wholly symbolic equation often arises in the study of
 mathematics.
 Principles (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:addition-property-of-equality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:multiplication-property-of-equality-part-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:multiplication-property-of-equality-part-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) are often used to solve such equations.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $XA-I=B$
\end_inset

 and we are interested in solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, for example.
 The process is the same as we would use if all the symbols represented
 numbers.
 We isolate the 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by adding to or multiplying both sides of the equation by appropriate matrices:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
XA-I+I & =B+I\\
XA & =B+I\\
XAA^{-1} & =(B+I)A^{-1}\\
X & =(B+I)A^{-1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Notice the careful right multiplication of both sides in the third line.
 It is not valid to left multiply one side of the equation while right multiplyi
ng the other.
 Also, we should note that this solution is only good as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is invertible!
\end_layout

