\begin_layout Standard
Just as we can imagine the product of two matrices as a collection of linear
 combinations of the rows of the righthand matrix, we can also imagine the
 product as a collection of linear combinations of the columns of the lefthand
 matrix.
 Thinking generally again, suppose we are given an arbitrary pair of matrices
 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $BA$
\end_inset

 is defined—that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 has the same number of columns as 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has rows, say 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 By definition the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\!c$
\end_inset

-entry of 
\begin_inset Formula $BA$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i,1}A_{1,c}+B_{i,2}A_{2,c}+\cdots+B_{i,n}A_{n,c}$
\end_inset

.
 Swapping the order of each product, 
\begin_inset Formula $(BA)_{i,c}=A_{1,c}B_{i,1}+A_{2,c}B_{i,2}+\cdots+A_{n,c}B_{i,n}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
(BA)_{1,c} & =A_{1,c}B_{1,1}+A_{2,c}B_{1,2}+\cdots+A_{n,c}B_{1,n}\nonumber \\
(BA)_{2,c} & =A_{1,c}B_{2,1}+A_{2,c}B_{2,2}+\cdots+A_{n,c}B_{2,n}\nonumber \\
 & \vdots\nonumber \\
(BA)_{m,c} & =A_{1,c}B_{m,1}+A_{2,c}B_{m,2}+\cdots+A_{n,c}B_{m,n}\label{eq:intermediary-step-mult-as-lin-comb-of-cols}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Reading these equations together (as columns of numbers) from left to right,
 they imply that column 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $BA$
\end_inset

 (the lefthand sides of the equations) equals 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1,c}$
\end_inset

 times column 1 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 (the first terms of the righthand sides) plus 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2,c}$
\end_inset

 times column 2 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 (the second terms of the righthand sides) plus 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{3,c}$
\end_inset

 times column 3 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 (the third terms of the righthand sides), and so on.
 In symbols,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
(BA)_{1,c}\\
(BA)_{2,c}\\
\vdots\\
(BA)_{m,c}
\end{array}\right]=A_{1,c}\left[\begin{array}{c}
B_{1,1}\\
B_{2,1}\\
\vdots\\
B_{m,1}
\end{array}\right]+A_{2,c}\left[\begin{array}{c}
B_{1,2}\\
B_{2,2}\\
\vdots\\
B_{m,2}
\end{array}\right]+\cdots+A_{n,c}\left[\begin{array}{c}
B_{1,n}\\
B_{2,n}\\
\vdots\\
B_{m,n}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

In other words, column 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $BA$
\end_inset

 is a linear combination of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 where the coefficients for the linear combination come from column 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 In short,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(BA)_{:,c}=A_{1,c}B_{:,1}+A_{2,c}B_{:,2}+\cdots+A_{n,c}B_{:,n}.\label{eq:matrix-prod-as-lin-comb-of-cols}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

